THE RISK:
{
 "id": "regulatory-stack-undercounted-serviceable",
 "title": "The serviceable haircut is priced against a 2019-era 3-item cert list while the binding 2024 stack is materially larger",
 "narrative": "serviceableFactor 0.55 is justified by three regimes: EN 50600, ecodesign 2019/424, CE/TÜV. The corpus surfaces a larger and newer stack — WEEE, RoHS, FCC, EORI customs registration, the EU Delegated Regulation 2024/1364 data-centre rating scheme, and the Energy Efficiency Directive 2024/1791's KPI and waste-heat-reuse disclosure duties on operators. Each missing artifact removes a buyer class from the entrant's reachable set: operators under EED reporting increasingly demand component-level efficiency documentation at procurement, and distributors will not list a product without WEEE/RoHS registration in each country. The regulatory-reach basis for the haircut is therefore stronger than the ledger represents, pushing the factor toward or below its 0.45 band edge — a level the band treats as a tail, not a central case.",
 "category": "fact",
 "targetNodes": [
  "serviceableFactor"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "EU Delegated Regulation 2024/1364 (rating scheme, effective May 2024) and EED 2024/1791 (KPI/WHR disclosure) land compliance duties on CE data-centre operators in 2024–26, pulling component-level energy documentation into procurement questionnaires",
   "refs": [
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c8",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c9"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "The entrant must clear WEEE, RoHS, CE/TÜV, EORI and provide EN 50600-aligned and ecodesign documentation per country; every artifact not held at launch removes the corresponding buyer class or geography from the serviceable set — a larger haircut than the 3-regime basis the node cites",
   "refs": [
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c10",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c7",
    "ledger:serviceableFactor"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The 0.55 centering reflects an undercounted barrier; the fuller stack pushes the serviceable share to or below the 0.45 band edge, and SAM definitions in the corpus explicitly include compliance/procurement reach as a gating dimension",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:serviceableFactor",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c12",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c13"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The ledger already applies a sub-1.0 haircut and names specific regulations — the box looks ticked. What hides the residual risk is vintage: the haircut's basis is a three-item list anchored in 2019-era instruments, while the binding additions (2024/1364, EED transposition into national law like Germany's EnEfG) postdate the derivation and never entered it.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "A compliance-gap audit showing the venture's launch SKUs satisfy the full artifact stack (WEEE registration, RoHS, CE/TÜV, EORI, ecodesign documentation) in Germany and the Netherlands by launch date, leaving no buyer class regulatory-foreclosed in the two geographies carrying 78% of the geo weight.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.45,
  "rationale": "The larger regulatory stack is documented in the digest, and the tension explicitly flags that the true barrier is stronger than the node's basis; uncertainty remains on how fast operator procurement operationalizes EED/1364 requirements into supplier questionnaires within 12 months [evidence revision: The existence, timing, and operator-facing nature of the fuller stack (2024/1364, EED 2024/1791, WEEE/RoHS market-access gates) are strongly corroborated by primary and expert sources, raising confidence in the regulatory-reach premise. However, the falsifiable link — that these duties translate within 12 months into component-level procurement foreclosure of buyer classes pushing serviceableFactor to/below 0.45 — remains only inferentially supported; 2024/1364 targets operators ≥500kW and EED implementation deadlines are staggered, so buyer-class foreclosure may lag. Modest upward revision from 0.4.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.4
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "serviceableFactor",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.4,
   "note": "Fuller 2024–25 compliance stack forecloses additional buyer classes/geographies beyond the 3-regime basis, pushing reach below the current band floor"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Component-level efficiency and sustainability documentation appearing as mandatory annexes in CE colo/enterprise RFQs",
   "where": "DE/NL data-centre fit-out RFQs and operator supplier-qualification questionnaires",
   "threshold": "≥2 RFQs in the first two quarters listing EED-KPI or 2024/1364-aligned documentation as a mandatory annex",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "National enforcement cadence of EED transposition on data-centre operators",
   "where": "German EnEfG data-centre reporting portal and BMWK implementation guidance releases",
   "threshold": "First enforcement/reporting deadline enforced on operators ≤ Year-1 window",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Commission a compliance-artifact gap audit mapping every instrument (WEEE, RoHS, CE/TÜV, EORI, 2019/424, 2024/1364, EED) to the buyer classes and geographies it gates, with cost and calendar time per artifact",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "serviceableFactor",
   "note": "Replaces the qualitative 3-regime haircut with a counted, dated reach model"
  },
  {
   "action": "Sequence certifications DE-first then NL (0.50 + 0.28 of the geo split) so that whatever serviceable share is achievable concentrates in the geographies carrying the capacity",
   "type": "operational",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Maximizes reachable SAM per compliance euro in the first 12 months"
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "New Data Centre Sustainability Reporting Obligations Introduced through EU 2024/1364",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "DLA Piper",
   "date": "2024-09-01",
   "excerpt": "establishes the information and key performance indicators (KPIs) to be reported to the European database by operators of data centres with an information technology energy demand of at least 500 KW ... entered into force on 6 June 2024",
   "url": "https://www.dlapiper.com/en-us/insights/publications/2024/09/new-data-centre-sustainability-reporting-obligations-introduced-through-eu-20241364-regulation",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "The EU's Energy Efficiency Directive and Its Impact on Datacenters",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Covington",
   "date": "2025-09",
   "excerpt": "imposes specific requirements on operators and owners of datacenters (disclosure of KPIs; WHR requirements) ... Member States must implement the EED's different requirements, which are subject to different deadlines",
   "url": "https://www.cov.com/-/media/files/corporate/publications/2025/04/the-eus-energy-efficiency-directive-and-its-impact-on-datacenters.pdf",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "WEEE Compliance Audits for Electronics Importers",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Deutsche Recycling Service GmbH",
   "date": "2025-02-12",
   "excerpt": "If you import electronics into the EU, you are considered a producer under the WEEE Directive. A compliance audit is not optional; it is a mandatory process to ensure you meet all legal requirements and avoid severe penalties.",
   "url": "https://deutsche-recycling.com/blog/weee-compliance-audit-for-electronics-importers/",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://eur-lex.europa.eu/eli/reg_del/2024/1364/oj/eng",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Commission Delegated Regulation (EU) 2024/1364 of 14 March 2024 on the first phase of the establishment of a common Union rating scheme for data centres"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.dlapiper.com/en-us/insights/publications/2024/09/new-data-centre-sustainability-reporting-obligations-introduced-through-eu-20241364-regulation",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "the information and key performance indicators (KPIs) to be reported to the European database by operators of data centres with an information technology energy demand of at least 500 KW"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://energy.ec.europa.eu/news/commission-adopts-eu-wide-scheme-rating-sustainability-data-centres-2024-03-15_en",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "this secondary legislation requires data centre operators to report the key performance indicators to the European database by 15 September 2024 and then by 15 May in 2025 and subsequent years"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.cov.com/-/media/files/corporate/publications/2025/04/the-eus-energy-efficiency-directive-and-its-impact-on-datacenters.pdf",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "It also imposes specific requirements on operators and owners of datacenters (disclosure of KPIs; WHR requirements)"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.tuv.com/usa/en/weee-rohs-services.html",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "If your products do not comply with these directives – aimed at the restriction of hazardous substances and waste – you could be banned from selling them on the European market."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://deutsche-recycling.com/blog/weee-compliance-audit-for-electronics-importers/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "If you import electronics into the EU, you are considered a producer under the WEEE Directive. A compliance audit is not optional; it is a mandatory process"
  }
 ]
}

